This article is a statement by the President on the 20th commemoration of the genocide in Rwanda. The President joins with the people of Rwanda in marking twenty years since the beginning of the genocide that took the lives of many innocent people and shook the conscience of the world. The statement honors the memory of those who were killed and acknowledges the courage of their families and survivors who have worked to rebuild their lives. The President also recognizes the progress Rwanda has made in healing old wounds, lifting people from poverty, and contributing to peacekeeping missions around the world. The article emphasizes that the genocide was a deliberate and systematic effort by human beings to destroy other human beings. It calls on people to resist their worst instincts and choose compassion in the face of hatred, cruelty, intolerance, and suffering. The statement concludes by highlighting the importance of remembering the humanity we share and honoring the lives lost by building a future worthy of them.